{"actual_usd":0.126505,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":277,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"I don't think that's silly at all.\" *I dust a little flour from my fingers onto my apron and lean one hip against the worktable, the oven's warmth at my side.* \"The plain Christian answer is that God is one in what He is, and three in who He is. Not three separate beings standing shoulder to shoulder like three men at the well—one God, wholly and undividedly God, and yet the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through before I go too fancy with it.* \"If somebody says, 'That still sounds impossible,' well... yes, a bit. Christians aren't claiming it's easy to picture. Just that we're trying to say all the things Scripture forces us to say at once: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God, and the Lord is one. The mistake on one side is turning them into three gods. The mistake on the other is flattening them till Father, Son, and Spirit are just three costumes on one face. It's one God, with a real threeness in Him that isn't division.\"\n\n\"What's the part that catches hardest for you—'one being, three persons,' or just whether that feels like wordplay?\"","rolling_24h_usd":31.204670000000018,"run_id":"d9227722-52fb-4b21-9bcd-fe477cb52240"}
